related_questions.question: What defines a true seal?
related_questions.snippet: True seals are termed "earless" because they lack an external ear flap, whereas in "eared" seals or sea lions an external ear flap is visible. There are other, somewhat subtle, differences between the front flippers of the two groups, but the hind flipper differences are noticeable.

related_questions.question: How can you tell if a seal is a true seal?
related_questions.snippet: “True” seals, also known as “earless” seals or simply “seals,” belong to a group of pinnipeds that have ear holes but lack an external ear flap. This includes species such as the harbor seal, endangered Hawaiian monk seal, and harp seal. Seals typically have a smaller body size compared to sea lions.

related_questions.question: Why are they called true seals?
related_questions.snippet: All the seal-/sea lion-looking animals (33 species to be exact) are called pinnipeds. Pinnipeds are divided into three families; True seals (Phocidae), Walruses (Odobenidae) and Eared seals (Otariidae). Walruses are easily identified by their tusks. True seals have no external ear flap but instead have ear holes.
